95
00:07:06.330 --> 00:07:07.360
pharma and biotech.

96
00:07:08.190 --> 00:07:11.740
I'm not sure how often you get to engage with the families whose work your

97
00:07:11.790 --> 00:07:15.510
work is impacting, but what I want to say to you is

98
00:07:15.610 --> 00:07:15.950
this.

99
00:07:17.650 --> 00:07:21.480
In our darkest hours and years, it is your work that is carving a window of

100
00:07:21.550 --> 00:07:24.390
light for families like ours to hope and dream in.

101
00:07:26.170 --> 00:07:29.230
In just two weeks, our beautiful son Sebas will turn seven years old.

102
00:07:30.290 --> 00:07:34.220
He still has four nodules in his lungs that are being monitored very closely,

103
00:07:34.890 --> 00:07:37.420
but we're deeply grateful that they've been stable for a year,

104
00:07:38.530 --> 00:07:41.330
and we don't take a single day of that for granted.

105
00:07:41.370 --> 00:07:41.820
For us,

106
00:07:42.650 --> 00:07:43.990
it means another day to fight.

107
00:07:46.750 --> 00:07:49.970
MEC affects both children and adults and is considered ultra-rare.

108
00:07:50.810 --> 00:07:54.410
The soft tissue version that Sebas has is even more rare, with just a handful of

109
00:07:54.450 --> 00:07:56.170
new cases each year in the US.

110
00:07:58.270 --> 00:08:01.930
In 2021, when Sebas was diagnosed, virtually nothing was known about

111
00:08:01.950 --> 00:08:05.690
MEC. There were no treatment protocols, no clinical trials, and no

112
00:08:05.770 --> 00:08:07.590
researchers focused on the disease.

113
00:08:08.970 --> 00:08:12.510
With 11 nodules in his lungs, we were told his prognosis was poor.

114
00:08:13.390 --> 00:08:15.160
It felt like stepping into darkness.

115
00:08:16.490 --> 00:08:20.210
But what gave us hope, what kept us moving, were other rare cancer

116
00:08:20.310 --> 00:08:23.210
patients and families who had walked similar paths before us.

117
00:08:24.230 --> 00:08:27.990
In the rare cancer world, patients and families are often the drivers of

118
00:08:28.050 --> 00:08:28.510
change.

119
00:08:30.010 --> 00:08:33.630
Over the past four years, we've learned that the challenge isn't just a lack of

120
00:08:33.691 --> 00:08:37.591
treatments. It's also the lack of the conditions that make research

121
00:08:37.650 --> 00:08:38.230
possible.

122
00:08:39.530 --> 00:08:43.451
Too few samples, too little data, too few disease models,

123
00:08:43.650 --> 00:08:46.030
too little coordination, too little funding.

124
00:08:46.970 --> 00:08:50.710
And that's why my wife Naomi and I co-founded Curemec from Sebas's

125
00:08:50.750 --> 00:08:51.490
hospital bed.

126
00:08:53.830 --> 00:08:55.600
One of the most important things we've learned,

127
00:08:56.490 --> 00:09:00.280
both in rare cancer and in my work as an environmental advocate, is that

128
00:09:00.310 --> 00:09:02.250
relationships are not separate from the work.

129
00:09:02.910 --> 00:09:04.570
Very often, they're what get it moving.

130
00:09:06.130 --> 00:09:09.560
One of Curemec's most important early contributions has been the partnerships and

131
00:09:09.630 --> 00:09:13.090
relationships we have helped cultivate between patient advocacy groups,

132
00:09:14.070 --> 00:09:16.570
clinicians, foundations, and researchers.

133
00:09:18.890 --> 00:09:22.870
And these relationships have led to exciting new collaborations, model

134
00:09:22.990 --> 00:09:26.350
sharing, scientific publications, inclusion

135
00:09:27.010 --> 00:09:30.580
of MEC in broader research efforts, and a growing willingness amongst

136
00:09:30.630 --> 00:09:34.290
partners to share information, tools, and expertise.

137
00:09:35.790 --> 00:09:39.670
And what feels both humbling and deeply hopeful to us is the team

138
00:09:39.710 --> 00:09:41.399
that has come together around this work.

139
00:09:42.330 --> 00:09:45.930
These are extraordinary scientists, people doing truly

140
00:09:45.970 --> 00:09:47.860
innovative and groundbreaking research.

141
00:09:48.810 --> 00:09:52.630
And what moves us the most is not only that they are willing to work with us,

142
00:09:53.210 --> 00:09:54.910
but that they are willing to work together.

143
00:09:56.970 --> 00:10:00.940
One example of that involves Dr. Ryan Roberts at Nationwide Children's and

144
00:10:00.970 --> 00:10:02.830
Dr. Taran Gujral at Fred Hutch.

145
00:10:03.970 --> 00:10:07.890
Dr. Roberts developed the world's only MEC PDX model and

146
00:10:07.970 --> 00:10:09.149
has been willing to share it.

147
00:10:10.150 --> 00:10:13.670
Dr. Gujral, who I had met at a Target Cancer symposium in Boston,

148
00:10:14.250 --> 00:10:17.850
developed an innovative systems pharmacology platform through his TRACER

149
00:10:17.870 --> 00:10:20.430
initiative and was willing to apply it to MEC.

150
00:10:21.450 --> 00:10:24.990
When those two pieces came together, a new opportunity opened up to test

151
00:10:25.030 --> 00:10:27.070
therapies and better understand the disease.

152
00:10:28.070 --> 00:10:31.390
And it's been this kind of generosity and willingness to work together that has

153
00:10:31.530 --> 00:10:33.190
shaped this entire journey for us.

154
00:10:34.150 --> 00:10:38.090
Because what we've learned is that progress in rare cancers rarely begins with

155
00:10:38.110 --> 00:10:41.070
a large research initiative or a major grant.

156
00:10:41.930 --> 00:10:42.990
It begins with people,

157
00:10:43.910 --> 00:10:47.850
with conversations, with scientists and funders who are willing to

158
00:10:47.970 --> 00:10:49.470
ask, "How can I help?"

159
00:10:51.830 --> 00:10:55.810
Last year at AACR, I met two researchers who asked that question and have since

160
00:10:55.850 --> 00:10:56.630
taken on MEC.

161
00:10:57.510 --> 00:11:01.310
Dr. Ryan New and his team conducted a retrospective study of 70 MEC

162
00:11:01.330 --> 00:11:04.870
patients at MD Anderson. And Dr. Elena

163
00:11:04.890 --> 00:11:08.760
Vasileva, now at Children's National, recently developed the

164
00:11:08.790 --> 00:11:11.150
first-ever genetic zebrafish model of MEC.

165
00:11:14.130 --> 00:11:16.720
That same spirit has shaped our partnership with funders.

166
00:11:17.720 --> 00:11:21.170
While our organization doesn't have enormous resources, we've tried to

167
00:11:22.390 --> 00:11:24.730
use every dollar we've raised as leverage.

168
00:11:25.670 --> 00:11:29.170
That has included partnering with larger foundations such as the RALLY

169
00:11:29.270 --> 00:11:32.730
Foundation and St. Baldrick's to co-fund MEC research projects,

170
00:11:33.450 --> 00:11:36.470
the first ever MEC-specific research grants ever awarded.

171
00:11:38.670 --> 00:11:41.690
And through our partnership with the Rare Cancer Research Foundation, we

172
00:11:42.250 --> 00:11:45.410
recently launched the first-ever MEC Biobank and Data Commons,

173
00:11:46.130 --> 00:11:49.810
critical resources that give patients and families a meaningful way to contribute

174
00:11:49.850 --> 00:11:53.570
to research by donating tumor tissue and sharing their

175
00:11:53.610 --> 00:11:54.550
medical histories.

176
00:11:55.750 --> 00:11:59.230
By building this infrastructure, we're making it easier for scientists to access

177
00:11:59.270 --> 00:12:03.020
the biospecimens and data they need to better understand MEC and

178
00:12:03.050 --> 00:12:04.810
explore new treatment possibilities.

179
00:12:05.950 --> 00:12:09.610
Together, these relationships and collaborations are helping lay the

180
00:12:09.670 --> 00:12:13.250
foundation for the first integrated research ecosystem for

181
00:12:13.270 --> 00:12:17.128
myoepithelial carcinoma.And this

182
00:12:17.138 --> 00:12:18.558
brings me to my closing ask.

183
00:12:19.418 --> 00:12:21.988
First, we need to connect with more MEC patients and families.

184
00:12:23.538 --> 00:12:26.658
Second, we need more biospecimens and associated clinical data,

185
00:12:27.138 --> 00:12:30.358
including fresh tissue, cryopreserved and frozen tissue,

186
00:12:30.838 --> 00:12:34.238
FFPE samples, and sequencing data.

187
00:12:34.318 --> 00:12:37.528
Access to samples remains one of the biggest barriers to progress.

188
00:12:38.658 --> 00:12:42.338
And third, we need more scientific partners, researchers willing to

189
00:12:42.378 --> 00:12:46.258
apply their tools, models, platforms, and ideas to this disease.

190
00:12:48.018 --> 00:12:50.098
If you're an oncologist or work in

191
00:12:50.458 --> 00:12:54.258
a hospital and can talk to the

192
00:12:54.298 --> 00:12:57.978
pathologists at your institution if they've ever seen MEC or if they have any

193
00:12:58.018 --> 00:13:01.818
samples, this could have an enormous impact on our efforts.

194
00:13:01.878 --> 00:13:05.798
With an ultra-rare cancer, every sample we find is invaluable to the work.

195
00:13:07.258 --> 00:13:10.978
If you think you might be able to help us either find samples or data, or if you

196
00:13:11.018 --> 00:13:14.958
want to collaborate, please come find me after the talk, or you can scan the

197
00:13:15.098 --> 00:13:19.058
QR code on the screen. We've created a simple form where you can let us know

198
00:13:19.098 --> 00:13:23.058
how you might be able to help. It would really mean the world to me to

199
00:13:23.118 --> 00:13:23.758
connect to you.

200
00:13:26.558 --> 00:13:30.478
My family is a soccer family. Both of my sons play, and I played

201
00:13:30.498 --> 00:13:31.598
for most of my life.

202
00:13:32.558 --> 00:13:36.158
Soccer is often called the most beautiful game, and one reason

203
00:13:36.218 --> 00:13:38.018
is that it's built on teamwork.

204
00:13:38.858 --> 00:13:42.038
No single player can carry the ball all the way to the goal every time.

205
00:13:42.878 --> 00:13:46.758
It takes passing, coordination, trust, and a shared

206
00:13:46.838 --> 00:13:47.797
sense of purpose.

207
00:13:48.918 --> 00:13:50.578
Rare cancer research is no different.

208
00:13:51.398 --> 00:13:54.898
In MEC, we need patients and families, scientists and clinicians,

209
00:13:55.218 --> 00:13:57.478
pathologists and funders all working together,

210
00:13:58.298 --> 00:14:01.578
each contributing in different ways but advancing towards the same goal.

211
00:14:02.618 --> 00:14:04.388
And that's what partnership looks like.

212
00:14:05.138 --> 00:14:09.068
It's how we move the ball forward. And for rare cancers like MEC, it's

213
00:14:09.098 --> 00:14:10.858
the only way we're going to make progress.

214
00:14:12.638 --> 00:14:14.738
And here's what I wouldn't have said just a year ago.

215
00:14:15.718 --> 00:14:19.188
Standing here today, I truly believe that this team we are

216
00:14:19.198 --> 00:14:21.098
building is going to win the cup.

217
00:14:22.318 --> 00:14:24.937
The only questions are, in what timeframe?

218
00:14:25.618 --> 00:14:29.558
Who else is going to be with us? And what will we have learned along the way?

219
00:14:30.678 --> 00:14:34.518
Not only about MEC science, but about what becomes possible

220
00:14:34.528 --> 00:14:38.498
when people choose to work together in a radically collaborative type of

221
00:14:38.558 --> 00:14:38.768
way,

222
00:14:39.658 --> 00:14:43.218
and how we will carry those lessons forward in the work we do, both

223
00:14:43.278 --> 00:14:45.438
professionally and personally.

224
00:14:46.578 --> 00:14:50.438
Because if we want to change the future for patients with MEC, we

225
00:14:50.478 --> 00:14:52.698
are only going to do it the way great teams do it,

226
00:14:53.618 --> 00:14:54.118
together,

227
00:14:54.978 --> 00:14:57.978
moving the ball forward one pass at a time.

228
00:14:58.978 --> 00:14:59.418
Thank you.

229
00:15:08.538 --> 00:15:12.318
So we'll take a few questions if you want, one or two questions.

230
00:15:13.538 --> 00:15:17.058
I have a question for you. So, this was really moving.

231
00:15:17.218 --> 00:15:21.167
I think this is really something, seeing parents and patients

232
00:15:21.198 --> 00:15:24.278
do this, really promoting rare diseases

233
00:15:25.318 --> 00:15:27.578
to the forefront and getting the research done.

234
00:15:29.138 --> 00:15:29.498
So,

235
00:15:30.558 --> 00:15:33.818
what did you think your biggest barrier is now?

236
00:15:34.358 --> 00:15:38.158
You've gotten this started, you've gotten a foot in the door

237
00:15:38.278 --> 00:15:40.598
type of thing, and a lot of things going on.

238
00:15:40.618 --> 00:15:42.618
What do you think your biggest challenge is today?

239
00:15:44.128 --> 00:15:48.098
Thanks for the question. I think one of the biggest barriers, as I mentioned

240
00:15:48.138 --> 00:15:50.378
in my presentation, is access to specimens.

241
00:15:51.018 --> 00:15:53.258
We really need any kind of specimen we can find.

242
00:15:53.318 --> 00:15:56.998
Even one specimen is going to make the difference for us.

243
00:15:57.438 --> 00:16:01.278
The PDX model and other models are critical to our work

244
00:16:01.318 --> 00:16:04.958
as well. The PDX is the only model that currently

245
00:16:04.978 --> 00:16:05.618
exists.

246
00:16:06.858 --> 00:16:10.418
And thankfully, thanks to Dr. Vassileva, now we have a genetic

247
00:16:10.478 --> 00:16:14.018
zebrafish model as well. So, I think access to

248
00:16:14.098 --> 00:16:17.898
specimens is the biggest

249
00:16:17.938 --> 00:16:21.558
barrier that we have at this time. The other thing is that we need to connect with

250
00:16:21.598 --> 00:16:25.258
more patients. So if any of you know oncologists who can

251
00:16:25.578 --> 00:16:29.398
at least give that patient our website, hopefully they'll

252
